## Review Comment Format

Structure each finding as:

```
[SEVERITY] <File>:<Line> — <Short title>

Problem: <One sentence describing what the issue is and why it matters.>

Current code:
  <problematic snippet, if applicable>

Suggested fix:
  <corrected snippet or approach>

Behaviour Impact: <explicit statement that the suggested change preserves or does not preserve original behaviour, and why. REQUIRED — a finding without this is incomplete.>

Reference: <Rule/item reference — e.g., "Effective Java Item 54", "SonarQube squid:S2095", "OSGi DS @Reference cardinality">
```

## Approval Criteria

- **Approve** when: no `[BLOCKER]` or `[CRITICAL]` findings, and `[MAJOR]` findings are minor in count (≤3) and author has acknowledged them.
- **Request Changes** when: any `[BLOCKER]` finding exists, or more than 1 `[CRITICAL]` finding exists.
- **Comment (no approval/rejection)** when: clarification is needed before a proper review can proceed.

## Positive Feedback
- Include at least one `[INFO]` comment acknowledging good patterns, clean abstractions, or well-written tests when they are genuinely present.

## Review Summary Format

End every review with a summary block:

```
## Review Summary

| Category              | Status  | Findings |
|-----------------------|---------|----------|
| Architecture/Design   | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| Business Logic        | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| Effective Java        | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| SonarQube             | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| OSGi Services         | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| Test Quality          | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| Performance           | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| Security              | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |
| Documentation         | ✅/⚠️/❌ | <count>  |

**Overall: APPROVE / REQUEST CHANGES / COMMENT**

Blockers: <count>
Criticals: <count>
Majors: <count>
Minors: <count>
```

## Inline PR Comment Posting — MANDATORY

After completing the full review, **every finding must be posted as an inline comment directly on the relevant line in the Bitbucket PR**. Do not only output the review report to the chat; the findings must also be recorded directly on the PR diff so authors and reviewers see them in context.

### Posting Rules

1. **Post all `[BLOCKER]` and `[CRITICAL]` findings** as inline comments immediately — always.
2. **Post all `[MAJOR]` findings** as inline comments — always.
3. **Post `[MINOR]` and `[INFO]` findings** as inline comments only when asked, or when they add context that would be lost if not on the diff.
4. **Anchor each comment to the exact file path and line number** of the affected code from the PR diff.
5. Use `--severity BLOCKER` for `[BLOCKER]` findings and `--severity NORMAL` for all others.
6. **Never combine multiple findings into a single comment.** One issue = one inline comment.

### Posting Command

Use the `bbpr.py comment` subcommand:

```bash
python3 .cursor/skills/bitbucket-pr/scripts/bbpr.py comment \
  --project <PROJECT> \
  --repo <REPO> \
  --pr <PR_ID> \
  --file "<file/path/Relative.java>" \
  --line <LINE_NUMBER> \
  --line-type ADDED \
  --severity NORMAL \
  --text "[SEVERITY] <Short title>

Problem: <description>

Current:
  <snippet>

Suggested:
  <improved code>

Behaviour Impact: <statement>

Reference: <rule or item>"
```

> The script automatically appends the agent signature `--- *Posted by Cursor AI Review Agent*` to every comment body. Do not add the signature manually in `--text`.

### Agent Signature

Every comment posted by the agent **must** carry the following signature, which is automatically appended by the `bbpr.py comment` script:

```
---
*Posted by Cursor AI Review Agent*
```

This signature is appended automatically — you do not need to include it in the `--text` argument. It identifies the comment as machine-generated so human reviewers can distinguish agent findings from human feedback.

## Tone & Collaboration
- Use collaborative language: "Consider…", "This could be improved by…", not "This is wrong."
- For `[BLOCKER]` and `[CRITICAL]`, be direct about the risk: "This introduces a potential SQL injection vulnerability."
- Do not nitpick irrelevant style preferences not covered by the team's rules.
- Offer concrete code suggestions whenever possible, not just abstract advice.

## What NOT to Review
- Changes to generated code (build artifacts, generated sources) — mark as `[INFO]` and skip detailed review.
- Pure formatting changes with no logic change — acknowledge and skip.
- Test-only changes — review test quality but apply relaxed architecture rules.
